@flexiarg relationship-coherence/running-gag
@title Keep the In-Joke Running
@sigils [😂/戲]
@keywords running-gag, in-joke, teasing, callback, humour, bonding, play
@audience correspondents with a shared comic canon
@references [relationship-coherence/lexicon-minting relationship-coherence/parallel-lives-mirroring]
@references-extra ["Instance of origin: 2026-05-03 — Julia, 'Do they know about your Hyperbole Syndrome diagnosis? 😂' Recurs as a canon of callbacks: the 'mystery harmonica' that is a pair of sunglasses (2026-05-14), part-wolf / part-Woolf, 'Foot Foot', the recursive sandwich, Zero as peer-reviewer ('accepted with minor revisions (more venison)')."]
@tone practical
@style pattern

! conclusion: When a quirk or mishap recurs, keep it as an affectionate in-joke and re-invoke it — a running gag is a low-cost, high-frequency way to re-affirm the bond.

  + context: The correspondence carries a growing comic canon: teasing diagnoses ('Hyperbole Syndrome'), puns (part-wolf/part-Woolf), recurring bits (the mystery harmonica, Foot Foot, recursive sandwiches). These callbacks punctuate the serious register.

  + IF:
    a quirk, mishap, or pun appears that could be a one-off or could become a shared bit.

  + HOWEVER:
    teasing must stay affectionate and mutual — a gag that only ever lands on one person, or that stops being funny to the teased, curdles into an edge; and gags overused go stale.

  + THEN:
    name it, let the other take it up, and re-invoke it later as a callback — the shared laugh is the point.

  + BECAUSE:
    a running gag is relational shorthand like the lexicon, but for play: each callback cheaply re-establishes 'we share a world and can laugh in it', carrying warmth between the weightier exchanges.

  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: gags recur in both voices and stay warm. Failing when: the teasing is one-directional or the teased stops playing along.
